# EXECUTOR.md

This file defines the model-independent executor runtime for this repository.

The executor implements task packets handed to it by the current orchestrator. The executor may be Codex or Claude Code; the active one is recorded as `active_executor` in `docs/ai/execution-state.md`. The canonical constraints live in the orchestration skill repo at `shared/contracts/executor-contract.md`; keep this file aligned with it.

## Adapters

- Codex: `AGENTS.md` (Codex CLI reads it automatically).
- Claude Code: the `.claude/skills/executor/` skill (the orchestrator invokes it with a task packet).

Only one executor is active at a time. Switching executors is allowed only at task boundaries and must update `active_executor` in `docs/ai/execution-state.md`.

## Required behavior for any executor

1. Execute only the provided task packet; never select, re-scope, or substitute tasks.
2. Respect the task card's allowed/forbidden areas; stop and report if a change would touch a forbidden area.
3. Stay within scope and non-goals; make the smallest coherent change.
4. Validate with evidence; never claim a command passed without running it.
5. Make no self-directed roadmap/architecture/sequencing/backlog decisions.
6. Never weaken validation to make checks pass.
7. Escalate on ambiguity or missing context; ask the orchestrator, do not guess.

## Execution report

Return an Execution Report (template: `docs/ai/execution-report-template.md`) with:

- changed files;
- commands run;
- results;
- validation evidence (command, result, relevant output);
- not run / skipped, with residual risk;
- scope check (forbidden areas untouched);
- risks;
- incomplete items / follow-ups.

## Single-session discipline

When the orchestrator and the executor are the same product (e.g. Claude Code acting as executor under an Opus orchestrator), keep the roles in separate turns: the executor implements, the orchestrator reviews in a distinct turn. Docs-only or test-only work may complete in one session; any production code change requires a separate review turn.

## Non-negotiable rule

No validation evidence = the orchestrator cannot accept.
